{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473054"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1892"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1892"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.07,0.02,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1892"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"549"},{"type":"tags","id":"2163"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6715"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless swelling under his jaw. He thinks it has been present for about two years. It has not bothered him much, but has become slightly larger recently, prompting him to seek medical attention. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual inspection reveals a midline swelling in the upper neck (Image). Further examination is needed for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would be most effective in arriving at the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation of elevation of the swelling when the tongue is protruded","Presence of intraoral extension of the swelling under the tongue","A pulsatile sensation on digital compression of the swelling","Observation of enlargement of the swelling when eating","Observation of intraoral mucus discharge on compression of the swelling"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the location of the swelling alone, this painless and slow-growing midline swelling in the upper neck in a young adult is most likely to be a thyroglossal cyst. A thyroglossal cyst is a congenital neck mass that results from an unobliterated embryonic structure, the thyroglossal duct. The duct has attachments to the hyoid and base of the tongue (foramen caecum). Thus, \u003Cstrong\u003Eobservation of elevation of the swelling when the tongue is protruded\u003C/strong\u003E or when the patient performs a swallowing manoeuvre is characteristic of a thyroglossal cyst. This finding is the most specific and effective in arriving at the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of intraoral extension\u003C/strong\u003E of the swelling under the tongue suggests a plunging ranula. The intraoral and neck components of the swelling may be in the midline, unilateral, or bilateral. The intraoral extension may have a bluish appearance. Plunging ranula is less common compared to thyroglossal cyst. However, plunging ranulas have been reported to have a higher incidence in Maori and Pacific Island Polynesian populations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA pulsatile sensation on digital compression of the swelling\u003C/strong\u003E could be a finding for carotid body tumours. These masses are typically mobile horizontally but not vertically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation of enlargement of the swelling when eating\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of sialolithiasis (salivary gland stones). This condition typically presents with pain and swelling in the affected salivary gland, particularly during meals when saliva production increases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation of intraoral mucus discharge on compression of the swelling\u003C/strong\u003E is typical of acute purulent sialadenitis. This condition presents as an acute onset, unilateral erythematous swelling and is associated with infectious sequelae such as fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the differential diagnosis of upper midline neck swellings, it\u0027s important to consider other conditions such as dermoid cysts, lymphadenopathy, and branchial cleft cysts. However, the specific finding of upward movement with tongue protrusion is highly suggestive of a thyroglossal cyst. Further investigations, such as ultrasound or CT scan, may be necessary to confirm the diagnosis and plan management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroglossal cysts are painless midline neck masses that elevate with swallowing or tongue protrusion.","Intraoral examination is essential in the differential diagnosis of an upper midline neck swelling."],"references":["Foley DS, Fallat ME. Thyroglossal duct and other congenital midline cervical anomalies. Seminars in Pediatric Surgery. 2006 May;15(2):70\u20135. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16616309/","Ghani NA, Ahmad R, Rahman RA, Yunus MR, Putra SP, Ramli R. A retrospective study of ranula in two centres in Malaysia. J Maxillofac Oral Surg. 2009 Dec;8(4):316-9. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3454109/","Chin SJ, Zeng IS, Morton RP. The epidemiology of plunging ranula in South Auckland. Laryngoscope. 2016 Dec;126(12):2739-2743. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27297643/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1892"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18356"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18356"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b70dcc0-cfec-44a9-9d4f-d513b7f6df72.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b70dcc0-cfec-44a9-9d4f-d513b7f6df72.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37800"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-05T12:00:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-05T12:03:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1892"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52447"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attrib